It is evident that the candidate chosen by Erdogan did not receive a great success: the former Minister of the Environment Murat Kurum>, faithful of the President and one of the most representative in view of the second generation of the party, but it seems not to have the charism and the ability to conquer the public.<br> &nbsp;
Born in 1976 in the capital Ankara, he completed his studies in different locations of the country as his father was a state official who was often transferred. Married and father of three children, a characteristic appreciated by the Turkish president, he graduated in Construction Engineering. Kurum has climbed positions within the party becoming the head of the Toki State Building Company, one of the pillars of Erdogan's power, first in Ankara and then in the European part of Istanbul. From 2018 to June 2023 he served as Minister of the Environment.
&nbsp;
It should however be pointed out that Kurum for years has been responsible for building renewal programmes > in the two largest cities of Turkey; programs aimed at replacing old buildings with houses built according to the anti-seism parameters foreseen after the 1999 earthquake. After the earthquake that devastated the south of the country on 6 February last, the fear is that the tragedy can be repeated in Istanbul. Several scientists have warned against the actual and imminent risk of a sisma of a degree exceeding 7>. Alarms that prompted Erdogan to accelerate construction renewal programs and the choice of Kurum should also be understood in this sense.&nbsp;
<h2>Imamoglu points to reconfirm</h2>
Will it be enough to defeat the mayor in charge Ekrem Imamoglu>, the man who 5 years ago inflicted on Erdogan the most violent battalion of his entire political career? Probably not. It is worth remembering what happened in 2019: after a first round in which Imamoglu imposed himself for a few thousand votes, in a city where the voting rights were 11.5 million, the Akp filed an appeal and returned to the polls.
&nbsp;
A decision badly digested by public opinion, which turned its back on the president's candidate, the little charismatic former prime minister Binali Yildirim> and chose Imamoglu, whose victory in the repetition was overwhelming (about 800 thousand votes more than the challenger). Imamoglu, as 5 years ago, is supported by the nationalists of Iyi parties, Kurum by the nationalists of Mhp. However, then, to be decisive for the victory of Imamoglu were the votes of the Kurds of the HP, but this time they have their own candidate.
&nbsp;
Imamoglu has still led a convincing campaign, it can count on a compact follow-up and charisma that from the stage allows him to establish a direct thread with the listener. A two-and-a-half-year sentence has even strengthened its position with a large part of the population, which saw a political move in the judges' decision. In the last election rounds, Erdogan's party did not get the positive results it had in the past in Istanbul.
<h2> The game is played in Ankara</h2>
In short, the game is played in the capital Ankara and in the metropolis on the Bosphorus in a country where the Aegean and Mediterranean coast has always been in the hands of the opposition, but it is unable to counter the overflow of the Erdogan party in Central Anatolia and on the Black Sea coast. In the cross the east by Kurdish majority, where the favorite is the Kurdish thread party Hdp, insidiated however by the Akp, which saw its consent grow enormously among the Kurds over the years.
&nbsp;
To see what will happen in the areas affected by the devastating earthquake of 6 February 2023. The party of Erdogan is strong of a overwhelming majority in many of the 11 provinces affected by the earthquake; a consensus confirmed in the presidential last May, three months after the earthquake. However important centers such as Antakya and Iskenderun are governed by mayors of the opposition party Chp and ended up in the sight for the management of the sisma. Administrations on which the anathema of Erdogan has also fallen, which invited the population to vote for their party "to facilitate reconstruction and post-sym recovery".

