AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The European Parliament is examining the allegations that a pro-Russian network would pay Euro MPs of at least six countries to spread pro-Cremlin propaganda and influence the June European Parliament's elections. "The President is aware of the case and is examining the specific allegations," said the spokesman of the President of the European Parliament, Roberta Metsola.
&nbsp;
The Czech Republic has announced on Wednesday that it has discovered a propaganda network linked to the Kremlin that is trying to influence the European Parliament and the next European elections of 6-9 June, in particular with messages contrary to the territorial integrity of Ukraine.
&nbsp;
"It is Members who receive money (from Russia)>. It is an external pressure, but there is cooperation from the inside. Also in our country, at the highest levels of our democratic institutions," said Belgian Prime Minister Alexander de Croo, President of the EU. Belgian secret services are working closely with Czechs to shed light on the story.
<br The media that reported the plot in the Czech Republic argue, citing sources of the national intelligence, that the Euro MPs involved in this case and that they would receive compensation for their participation would prove from Germany, France, Poland, the Netherlands, Belgium and Hungary, even if they do not appoint any specific legislator.
&nbsp;
The press service of the European Parliament has explained that the institution is already examining the accusations regarding the site "Voice of Europe" >, around which the network of pro-Russian influence was developed, and said that it could limit the access to the site by the structures of the European Parliament, as it has already done with other sanctions from the EU, for spreading false narratives on the war in Ukraine.><br> In a February resolution this year, the European Parliament itself warned against the "continuous efforts of Russia to weaken European democracy" and its recruitment of members of the European Parliament as agents of influence or the use of European political parties " acting as a propaganda of the Kremlin" as an amp at the service of its interests.
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The first reactions within the European Chamber have come from the Green and Liberal groups, with the leaders calling on the President of the European Parliament to start a rapid and transparent investigation > that reveals the scope of the flu-Russian operation and allows action against the Euro MPs involved.
&nbsp;
"European elections are in ten weeks. We need to make sure that the Russians don't pay any of the candidates", asked Dutch environmentalist Bas Eickhout, while his German colleague, Terry Reintke, asked for a "serious punishment" for the Euro MPs involved.
&nbsp;
"If the Euro MPs in office or candidates for the next European elections have received money from the Russian government or its representatives, we must report it and we must act. European voters need to know whether their MEPs or candidates for the next elections are working with the support of Russia or its representatives," said Renew Europe's Liberal Leader, Valerie Hayer.<br> The Group called on the European Parliament to discuss the scandal in the next plenary session, which will be held on 10 and 11 April in Brussels, and called on the Vice-President of the European Commission for Values, Vera Jourova, to participate in the debate.
&nbsp;
The European Parliament has a number of sanctions against Euro MPs for violations of the internal rules of ethics and transparency, ranging from the revocation of the daily allowance for a maximum of 60 days, to the temporary suspension of parliamentary activity, to the prohibition of &nbsp; to represent the institution in different locations or the limitation of access to confidential information. The European Parliament cannot withdraw the seat of any Member, since it is responsible for each Member State, or prevent them from running for the next June European elections.&nbsp;
